<font color="#FF0000">USMC TRAINING &amp; SURVIVAL </font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 27 13:36:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I joined the corps because I knew that I would be going to Vietnam. I wanted the best training possible so that I would be able to survive. <br>
I sucked in all in from the time my feet hit the deck at MCRD, I was there to learn how to survive. Saw the weak get left behind in training , they disappeared and we never saw them again. I feared failing. In Nam while under fire the words of some high school teacher, some American Parade, American made product or the words  Sgt. Nelson spoke to us in boot camp helped get me through. <br><br>
From Dreams of Glory&quot; (C) 1997 Cook Barela<br>
(waiting to board the plane for Vietnam)<br><br>
SENTIMENTAL JOURNEY<br>
El Toro Marine Corps Air Base<br>
El Toro, California<br>
1230 Hours, Tuesday, June 13, 1967<br><br>
... The words of Sgt. Nelson, our drill instructor at MCRD were echoing through my mind. <br>
&quot;I've been south, I spend my thirteen months overseas.  I ain't going there. You are. That's the land of no postage stamps. The only bennie's you will receive in Vietnam is that you will be able to write home for free.  You won't have to put a stamp on the envelope to send a letter home.  You just write, free on the envelope where the stamps goes and Uncle Sam sends it home without cost to you.  It's the same if you get killed in Viet Nam, the Corps sends your body back home in a body bag for free. They just write on it, Dead Marine and ship it home for free, it won't cost your parents one cent.&quot; <br><br>
Sgt. Nelson often warned us to stay awake and to pay close attention in class, especially in hand to hand combat training, in the cleaning of our weapons, and in learning how to shoot and kill the enemy. During the rigorous recruit training and long hours we spent in physical exercising and mental training many recruits would often began to nod off during long periods of lectures from dull instructors in our classrooms. Sgt. Nelson would come up behind those recruits, slap them aside the head and yell at them.<br>
&quot;Marine, if you want to stay alive, pay close attention in class. If you fall asleep in combat, your dead! Dead! Dead! Dead!!  Marines your going to Vietnam to kill, not to be killed. Marines won't win this war by dying in the country of Viet Nam. The Vietnamese people don't want you to die for them. Uncle Sam doesn't want you to die for him. I don't want you to die in Viet Nam.  All Uncle Sam wants you to do in Viet Nam is kill VC (Viet Cong). Just kill the enemy. You won't win the war by getting laid by the local village whore. You'll get the black-syph and the black-syph will eat away your pecker and you'll die. If you die  in Viet Nam, the Marine Corps Commandant will bust me down to buck private, because he'll say I didn't train you right. Marine, you better not die because you did something stupid in Viet Nam. You better not die because you didn't pay attention in my boot camp. Marine, if you die in Viet Nam, for some dumb reason, I'll find you when I get to heaven and I'll kick your ass for making me look bad in front of the Marine Corps Commandant. I don't want to look bad in front of the Marine Corps Commandant. Do you hear me Marine?&quot; <br>
&quot;YES, SIR,&quot; the platoon always loudly shouted back.<br><br>
THANK YOU SGT. NELSON<br><br>
It paid off in the field while under combat, reminds me of the movie Forest Gump, where he first arrives and his lieutenant tells him to keep his feet dry and to not get killed. Forest answers by saying, Sure hope I don't let him down.<br>

